        <!-- Section 1 -->
        <h2 id="do-you-need">Do You Really Need a Lobbyist?</h2>

        <p>
          Let's be honest: lobbyists aren't cheap. Before you start shopping around, you need to answer a fundamental question:
          <em>Can you accomplish your goals without one?</em>
        </p>

        <p><strong>You probably need a lobbyist if:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>The stakes are high.</strong> We're talking regulations that could cost you millions, legislation that threatens your entire business model, or policy changes that affect your industry's future.</li>
          <li><strong>You lack relationships.</strong> You don't have direct access to key legislators, committee chairs, or agency heads. Your emails get ignored and your calls aren't returned.</li>
          <li><strong>The issue is complex.</strong> The policy landscape is technical, involves multiple agencies, or requires coordination across different legislative committees.</li>
          <li><strong>Time is short.</strong> Legislative sessions move fastâ€”only 140 days every two years for regular sessions. You can't afford to learn the ropes while your issue dies in committee.</li>
          <li><strong>You're outgunned.</strong> Your opponents already have lobbyists, and you're bringing a butter knife to a lobbying gunfight.</li>
        </ul>

        <p><strong>You might NOT need a lobbyist if:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>Your issue has broad, bipartisan support and will likely pass anyway</li>
          <li>You have strong existing relationships with key decision-makers</li>
          <li>Your organization has in-house government relations staff</li>
          <li>You're dealing with a straightforward, non-controversial issue</li>
          <li>Budget constraints make it impossible (though sometimes doing nothing costs more)</li>
        </ul>

        <div class="not-prose bg-amber-50 border-l-4 border-amber-500 p-6 my-8">
          <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-amber-900 mt-0 mb-2">Reality Check</h3>
          <p class="text-sm text-amber-900 m-0">
            Grassroots advocacy and coalition-building can sometimes achieve what paid lobbyists doâ€”but it takes time,
            organization, and sustained effort. If you've got a tight deadline or a small team, a lobbyist might be your
            only realistic option.
          </p>
        </div>

        <!-- Section 2 -->
        <h2 id="when-to-hire">When to Hire a Lobbyist (Timing Matters)</h2>

        <p>
          Texas operates on a biennial legislative schedule. The Legislature meets for 140 days starting in January of odd-numbered years.
          If you wait until the session starts to hire a lobbyist, you're already behind.
        </p>

        <p><strong>Ideal timeline:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>6-12 months before session:</strong> Start your search. Give your lobbyist time to build relationships, understand your issue, and develop strategy.</li>
          <li><strong>3-6 months before session:</strong> Contract should be signed. Your lobbyist should be meeting with legislators and their staff.</li>
          <li><strong>Session starts:</strong> Your lobbyist hits the ground running with established relationships and a clear game plan.</li>
        </ul>

        <p>
          <strong>Off-session work matters too.</strong> Some of the most effective lobbying happens between sessions when legislators
          are back in their districts, interim committees are studying issues, and you can build relationships without the chaos
          of session. Many lobbyists work year-round, not just during the 140-day sprint.
        </p>

        <!-- Section 3 -->
        <h2 id="define-goals">Define Your Goals & Budget</h2>

        <p>
          Before you talk to a single lobbyist, get crystal clear on what you're trying to accomplish and what you're willing to spend.
        </p>

        <h3>Setting Clear Goals</h3>
        <p>Vague goals lead to vague results. Instead of "we want to improve healthcare policy," try:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>"Kill HB 1234 that would impose new regulations on our industry"</li>
          <li>"Pass SB 567 to extend our tax credit program for three more years"</li>
          <li>"Amend SB 890 to include an exemption for small businesses under 50 employees"</li>
          <li>"Secure $2 million in appropriations for our nonprofit's program"</li>
          <li>"Build relationships with the Senate Health & Human Services Committee for next session"</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Budget Reality</h3>
        <p>
          Lobbying isn't cheap, but it's often cheaper than the alternative (losing a fight that costs your business millions).
          Typical Texas lobbying costs:
        </p>

