          <strong>Add to that:</strong> expenses (travel, event tickets, meeting costs), potential success bonuses,
          and coalition/grassroots support costs. Budget $50K-$100K minimum for a session if you're serious.
        </p>

        <!-- Section 4 -->
        <h2 id="find-lobbyist">How to Find the Right Lobbyist</h2>

        <p>Now for the fun part: actually finding someone to hire. You've got several options:</p>

        <h3>1. Start with TexasLobby.org (Obviously)</h3>
        <p>
          We've got {totalLobbyists.toLocaleString()} active lobbyists you can browse by <a href="/subjects">subject area</a>,
          <a href="/cities">city</a>, or <a href="/industries">industry</a>. {claimedCount.toLocaleString()} have claimed their profiles with
          detailed bios, client lists, and contact information.
        </p>

        <p><strong>How to search effectively:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Filter by subject area:</strong> If your issue is healthcare-related, search <a href="/subjects/healthcare">Healthcare lobbyists</a></li>
          <li><strong>Look at client lists:</strong> Have they represented similar organizations? That's a good sign.</li>
          <li><strong>Check their cities:</strong> Austin-based lobbyists tend to have stronger Capitol connections, but regional lobbyists might have better local relationships</li>
          <li><strong>Premium/Featured badges matter:</strong> Lobbyists who invest in their profiles are usually more established</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>2. Ask for Referrals</h3>
        <p>
          Talk to trade associations, industry groups, or businesses in your sector. Who do they use? Who do they trust?
          Personal referrals carry weight because reputation is everything in lobbying.
        </p>

        <h3>3. Check Texas Ethics Commission Records</h3>
        <p>
          All lobbyists must register with the Texas Ethics Commission. You can see who's representing whom,
          though the data is clunky and hard to navigate (which is why we built TexasLobby.org).
        </p>

        <h3>4. Attend Legislative Events</h3>
        <p>
          Go to committee hearings, industry conferences, or Capitol receptions during session. Watch who's effective,
          who legislators actually listen to, and who seems to know what they're doing.
        </p>

        <!-- Section 5 -->
        <h2 id="evaluate">Evaluating Lobbyist Credentials</h2>

        <p>You've got a list of potential lobbyists. Now you need to separate the pros from the pretenders.</p>

        <h3>What to Look For:</h3>

        <p><strong>1. Relevant Experience</strong></p>
        <p>
          Have they worked on your type of issue before? A healthcare lobbyist might be useless on energy policy.
          Check their client list and ask for specific examples of similar work.
        </p>

        <p><strong>2. Relationships That Matter</strong></p>
        <p>
          Do they have access to the legislators and committee chairs who control your issue's fate? Ask directly:
          "How well do you know the chair of the Senate Business & Commerce Committee?" A good lobbyist will give specifics.
        </p>

        <p><strong>3. Track Record</strong></p>
        <p>
          What have they actually accomplished? Don't just accept "we worked on 15 bills." Ask: "How many passed?
          How many were your client's top priority? What happened when you lost?"
        </p>

        <p><strong>4. Reputation & Ethics</strong></p>
        <p>
          Lobbyists live and die by their reputations. Google them. Check for any ethics violations or disciplinary actions.
          Ask aroundâ€”the Texas lobbying community is small and people talk.
        </p>

        <p><strong>5. Communication Style</strong></p>
        <p>
          You'll be working closely with this person. Do they explain things clearly? Return calls promptly?
          Make you feel heard? Chemistry matters.
        </p>

        <div class="not-prose bg-green-50 border-l-4 border-green-500 p-6 my-8">
          <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-green-900 mt-0 mb-2">Pro Tip: The "Former Legislator" Myth</h3>
          <p class="text-sm text-green-900 m-0">
            Former legislators can make great lobbyistsâ€”but not always. Some trade on old relationships without doing the work.
            Others adapt brilliantly to advocacy. Judge them on current effectiveness, not past titles.
          </p>
        </div>

        <!-- Section 6 -->
        <h2 id="interview">Questions to Ask During Interviews</h2>

        <p>
          You're not hiring someone to mow your lawn. This is a strategic relationship that could determine whether
          your organization thrives or faces regulatory disaster. Ask tough questions.
        </p>

        <h3>About Their Experience:</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>"Can you walk me through a recent client engagement similar to ours? What was the outcome?"</li>
          <li>"What's your success rate on bills you've actively supported or opposed?"</li>
          <li>"Have you ever worked on both sides of an issue? How do you handle conflicts of interest?"</li>
          <li>"What's the biggest lobbying failure you've had, and what did you learn from it?"</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>About Relationships & Strategy:</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>"Which legislators do you have the strongest relationships with?"</li>
          <li>"How would you approach our specific issue?"</li>
          <li>"Who are the key decision-makers we need to influence?"</li>
          <li>"What opposition do you anticipate, and how would you counter it?"</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>About Logistics & Communication:</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>"How often will you update us on progress?"</li>
          <li>"What's your typical response time for questions or urgent issues?"</li>
          <li>"Will you personally handle our account, or will we work with junior staff?"</li>
          <li>"Do you have other clients with potential conflicts to our position?"</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>About Money:</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>"What's your fee structureâ€”monthly retainer, hourly, or contingency?"</li>
          <li>"What expenses should we expect beyond your fee?"</li>
          <li>"Do you offer success bonuses, and how are they structured?"</li>
          <li>"What happens if we need to pause or terminate the contract?"</li>
        </ul>

        <!-- Section 7 -->
        <h2 id="red-flags">Red Flags to Avoid</h2>

        <p>Some warning signs that a lobbyist might not be worth your money:</p>

        <div class="not-prose my-8">
          <div class="bg-red-50 border border-red-200 rounded-lg p-6">
            <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-red-900 mt-0 mb-4">ðŸš© Warning Signs</h3>
            <ul class="space-y-3 m-0">
              <li class="flex items-start gap-3">
                <span class="text-red-600 font-bold flex-shrink-0">Ã—</span>
                <span class="text-sm text-red-900"><strong>Guarantees results:</strong> No lobbyist can guarantee a bill will pass. If they promise it, they're lying.</span>
              </li>
              <li class="flex items-start gap-3">
                <span class="text-red-600 font-bold flex-shrink-0">Ã—</span>
                <span class="text-sm text-red-900"><strong>Won't provide references:</strong> Established lobbyists have satisfied clients who'll vouch for them.</span>
              </li>
              <li class="flex items-start gap-3">
                <span class="text-red-600 font-bold flex-shrink-0">Ã—</span>
                <span class="text-sm text-red-900"><strong>Vague about their approach:</strong> Good lobbyists have specific strategies, not hand-wavy generalities.</span>
              </li>
              <li class="flex items-start gap-3">
                <span class="text-red-600 font-bold flex-shrink-0">Ã—</span>
                <span class="text-sm text-red-900"><strong>Too many conflicts:</strong> If they represent your competitors or opposing interests, walk away.</span>
              </li>
              <li class="flex items-start gap-3">
                <span class="text-red-600 font-bold flex-shrink-0">Ã—</span>
                <span class="text-sm text-red-900"><strong>Poor communication:</strong> If they're hard to reach during the hiring process, imagine how it'll be when you're paying them.</span>
              </li>
              <li class="flex items-start gap-3">
                <span class="text-red-600 font-bold flex-shrink-0">Ã—</span>
                <span class="text-sm text-red-900"><strong>Suspiciously cheap:</strong> Bottom-barrel pricing often means bottom-barrel results.</span>
              </li>
              <li class="flex items-start gap-3">
                <span class="text-red-600 font-bold flex-shrink-0">Ã—</span>
                <span class="text-sm text-red-900"><strong>Ethics concerns:</strong> Any hint of past violations or shady practices should be disqualifying.</span>
              </li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Section 8 -->
        <h2 id="contracts">Understanding Lobbying Contracts</h2>

        <p>You've found your lobbyist. Now it's time to put everything in writing. Don't skim the contractâ€”this matters.</p>

        <h3>Key Contract Elements:</h3>

        <p><strong>1. Scope of Work</strong></p>
        <p>
          Be specific about what they're doing. "General lobbying services" is too vague. List specific bills,
          legislators to target, committees to monitor, and deliverables (weekly reports, strategy memos, etc.).
        </p>

        <p><strong>2. Compensation Structure</strong></p>
        <p>Most common models:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Monthly Retainer:</strong> Fixed monthly fee, most common for ongoing relationships</li>
          <li><strong>Project-Based:</strong> Flat fee for a specific legislative session or issue</li>
          <li><strong>Hourly:</strong> Less common in Texas, more typical for consulting work</li>
          <li><strong>Success Bonuses:</strong> Additional payment if specific goals are achieved (beware ethical implications)</li>
        </ul>

        <p><strong>3. Expenses</strong></p>
        <p>
          Clarify what's included in the retainer vs. what's billed separately. Common expenses: travel to Austin,
          event tickets, research costs, coalition membership fees. Get a cap on monthly expenses or require pre-approval.
        </p>

        <p><strong>4. Term & Termination</strong></p>
        <p>
          How long does the contract run? Can either party terminate it early? What happens to unused retainer funds?
          What's the notice period? Build in flexibility in case things aren't working out.
        </p>

        <p><strong>5. Reporting & Communication</strong></p>
        <p>
          Specify how often you'll receive updates (weekly emails? monthly calls?), what information will be included,
          and who your primary contact is.
        </p>

        <p><strong>6. Conflicts of Interest</strong></p>
        <p>
          The lobbyist should disclose any current or potential conflicts and agree not to take on conflicting clients
          without your consent.
        </p>

        <p><strong>7. Confidentiality</strong></p>
        <p>
          Protect sensitive business information, strategic plans, and internal deliberations.
        </p>

        <div class="not-prose bg-blue-50 border-l-4 border-blue-500 p-6 my-8">
          <p class="text-sm text-blue-900 m-0">
            <strong>Legal Review:</strong> Have your attorney review the contract before signing. Lobbying contracts
            involve legal nuances around representation, fees, and ethics that deserve professional scrutiny.
          </p>
        </div>

